Chapter 2 – Part 8: Custom 404 Error Page

When a user visits a URL that does not exist (example: /abc), 
Flask normally shows its default 404 page.
In this part, we override it with our own template.

# 1) Error handler in routes.py
      @app.errorhandler(404)
      def error404(error):
          return render_template('errorPage.html', pageTitle='OOPs where am i??'), 404

What this means
@app.errorhandler(404) tells Flask:
“When a 404 happens, call this function.”

Flask passes an error object into the function, so the function must accept one argument.
, 404 ensures the HTTP response code stays 404, not 200.

# 2) Create templates/errorPage.html
    {% extends "base.html" %}
    {% block content %}
          <h1>This page does not exists</h1>
          <p>I am 404- Nice to meet you</p>
    {% endblock %}

Why this is best
It automatically gets:
CSS, navigation menu, layout structure
No duplicate HTML boilerplate

# 3) Test your 404 page
Run your app and visit a route that doesn’t exist:
      /random
      /hello123
      /thispagedoesnotexist
A custome page is seen, and logs shows 404 returned.

Optional upgrade (shows which URL was wrong)
To show the wrong path, pass it from Flask.

Update handler:
      from flask import request
      
      @app.errorhandler(404)
      def error404(error):
          return render_template(
              'errorPage.html',
              pageTitle='OOPs where am i??',
              path=request.path
          ), 404

Then in template:
<p>You tried to access: <strong>{{ path }}</strong></p>

